      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(acp): skip oneshot sessions during startup identity reconcile",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nGateway startup identity reconciliation attempts to resolve pending ACP session identities. Oneshot sessions are terminal by nature, but their identity often remains `pending` after completion. The reconcile loop tries to ensure a runtime handle for each one, which fails and produces misleading warnings:\n\n```text\n[gateway] acp startup identity reconcile (renderer=v1): checked=7 resolved=0 failed=7\n```\n\nThis makes it look like ACP/Codex/Claude agent routing is broken when fresh sessions are healthy.\n\n## Fix\n\nSkip sessions with `mode === \"oneshot\"` in `runManagerStartupIdentityReconcile` so the startup scan only processes persistent sessions that may genuinely need identity resolution.\n\n## Changed files\n\n- `src/acp/control-plane/manager.startup-identity-reconcile.ts` -- Added `session.acp.mode === \"oneshot\"` guard after the session key check\n- `src/acp/control-plane/manager.startup-identity-reconcile.test.ts` -- Regression test: oneshot session with pending identity is skipped (checked=0, no ensure/getStatus calls)\n\n## Overlap with #85399\n\nPR #85399 (bound startup sidecar fanout) rewrites the same startup reconcile loop. This PR's guard (`session.acp.mode === \"oneshot\" -> continue`) is an independent behavior concern from #85399's fanout bounding. Both changes apply cleanly on the same function. Landing order should not matter as long as the guard is preserved during any rebase.\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\nBehavior addressed: ACP startup identity reconciliation processes oneshot sessions unnecessarily, producing misleading \"checked=N resolved=0 failed=N\" warnings and making ensure/reconcile calls for ephemeral sessions that will never need identity resolution.\n\nReal environment tested: macOS 15.5, Node v22.19, OpenClaw built from branch `fix/acp-reconcile-skip-oneshot` at `/tmp/proof-86711`.\n\nExact steps or command run after this patch:\n\nStep 1. Build from branch and verify the oneshot guard is active in compiled production code.\nStep 2. Exercise the production `runManagerStartupIdentityReconcile` with three mock ACP sessions: one oneshot with pending identity, one persistent with pending identity, and one persistent with already-resolved identity.\n\nEvidence after fix: terminal output from the patched build:\n\nThe oneshot guard is active in the compiled production bundle:\n\n```console\n$ grep -n -B1 -A2 'session.acp.mode.*oneshot.*continue' dist/manager-mG2xJXhX.js\n1448:for (const session of acpSessions) {\n1449-if (!session.acp || !session.sessionKey) continue;\n1450:if (session.acp.mode === \"oneshot\") continue;\n1451-const currentIdentity = resolveSessionIdentityFromMeta(session.acp);\n1452-if (!isSessionIdentityPending(currentIdentity) || !identityHasStableSessionId(currentIdentity)) continue;\n```\n\nRuntime exercise of the production function confirms the guard works:\n\n```console\n$ npx tsx proof-86711.ts\n\nInput sessions:\n  [acp:oneshot-session-A] mode=oneshot, identity.state=pending\n  [acp:persistent-session-B] mode=persistent, identity.state=pending\n  [acp:persistent-session-C] mode=persistent, identity.state=resolved\n\n  -> withSessionActor called for: acp:persistent-session-B\n\n--- Results ---\n  checked:  1\n  resolved: 1\n  failed:   0\n\n--- Sessions that entered reconciliation (withSessionActor) ---\n  acp:persistent-session-B\n\n--- Verification ---\n  Oneshot session SKIPPED (not reconciled):  PASS\n  Persistent pending session reconciled:     PASS\n  Persistent resolved session skipped:       PASS\n  checked === 1 (only persistent-pending):   PASS\n  resolved === 1:                            PASS\n  failed === 0:                              PASS\n\n== ALL CHECKS PASSED ==\nThe oneshot guard at line 43-44 correctly skips oneshot sessions\nwhile persistent sessions with pending identities are still reconciled.\n```\n\nObserved result after fix: The compiled production code at `dist/manager-mG2xJXhX.js:1450` contains the oneshot guard `if (session.acp.mode === \"oneshot\") continue;` which skips oneshot sessions before the identity check. Runtime exercise of the production `runManagerStartupIdentityReconcile` confirms only `acp:persistent-session-B` (mode=persistent, identity.state=pending) triggers reconciliation. The oneshot session `acp:oneshot-session-A` never enters the loop body despite having a pending identity. Final counters: `checked=1 resolved=1 failed=0`, which produces a clean startup log instead of the misleading `checked=7 resolved=0 failed=7`.\n\nWhat was not tested: Live gateway startup with real persisted stale oneshot sessions from a multi-backend ACP deployment. That scenario requires an active ACP backend with accumulated historical Codex/Claude session data and would show the startup log line changing from `checked=N failed=N` to `checked=M` where M excludes oneshot rows.\n\n\n",
        "branch": "fix/acp-reconcile-skip-oneshot",
